{"Title": "Majority and minority ethnic status adolescents' bystander responses to racism in school", "Year": 2017, "Source": "J. Community Appl. Soc. Psychol.", "Volume": "27", "Issue": 5, "Art.No": null, "PageStart": 374, "PageEnd": 380, "CitedBy": 5, "DOI": "10.1002/casp.2313", "Link": "https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85020305608&origin=inward", "Abstract": "Copyright \u00a9 2017 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.Twelve to 15-year-olds (N = 1,100) from majority and minority ethnic backgrounds, living in an ethnically diverse area in the UK, read a hypothetical scenario about verbal racism in school and indicated their bystander responses (prosocial, aggressive, and passive). Findings showed that age, ethnicity, cross-group friendships, and ethnic socialisation predicted their bystander responses.", "AuthorKeywords": ["adolescence", "bias-based bullying", "bystander", "cross-group friendship", "development", "ethnic socialisation", "minority and majority status", "racism"], "IndexKeywords": null, "DocumentType": "Journal", "PublicationStage": null, "OpenAccess": 2, "EID": "2-s2.0-85020305608", "SubjectAreas": [["Social Psychology", "PSYC", "3207"], ["Sociology and Political Science", "SOCI", "3312"]], "AuthorData": {"50262839800": {"Name": "Palmer S.B.", "AuthorID": "50262839800", "AffiliationID": "60006242", "AffiliationName": "UCL Institute of Education"}, "9240351900": {"Name": "Cameron L.", "AuthorID": "9240351900", "AffiliationID": "60010818", "AffiliationName": "University of Kent"}, "6701862409": {"Name": "Rutland A.", "AuthorID": "6701862409", "AffiliationID": "60010964", "AffiliationName": "Goldsmiths, University of London"}, "57190119345": {"Name": "Blake B.", "AuthorID": "57190119345", "AffiliationID": "119193722", "AffiliationName": "Rights & Equality Sandwell"}}}